<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-least-squares" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Linear regression and the least squares method</title>
    <p>
        Linear regression is a method in mathematics, statistics and machine learning that aims to describe a linear relationship between a collection of independent variables and one dependent variable. The term regression originates from the 19th century study led by Francis Galton where he first observed the statistical phenomenon that came to be known as <em>regression towards the mean</em>. Galton found that certain some extreme characteristics are not fully passed from parents to their offspring. Instead, the offspring's characteristic <em>regress towards the mean</em>. Using data measuring the height of parents and their children, Galton was able to quantify this regression for the case of height. We will be use Galton's data later to illustrate the process of linear regression.
    </p>
    <p>
        We will need the following result.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-dist-proj">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>V</m> be a linear subspace of <m>\R^n</m>, and let <m>\bv</m> be a vector in <m>\R^n</m>. The vector in <m>V</m> that is the closest to <m>\bv</m> is <m>\pr_V(\bv)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                We need to show that if <m>\bw</m> is any other vector in <m>V</m>, then
                <me>
                    \lVert\bv-\bw\rVert &gt; \lVert\bv-\pr_V(\bv)\rVert
                </me>, or equivalently
                <me>
                    \lVert\bv-\bw\rVert^2 &gt; \lVert\bv-\pr_V(\bv)\rVert^2
                </me>.
                Since we are assuming that <m>\bw</m> is a vector in <m>V</m> that is different from <m>\pr_V(\bv)</m>, we know that the vector <m>\bu=\bw-\pr_V(\bv)</m> lies in <m>V</m> and is non-zero. In particular, <m>\lVert\bu\rVert &gt; 0</m>. Now,
                <me>
                    \lVert\bv-\bw\rVert^2 = (\bv-\bw)\cdot(\bv-\bw)= (\bv-\pr_V(\bv)-\bu)\cdot(\bv-\pr_V(\bv)-\bu).
                </me>.
                Expanding the right-hand side of this equation, we find that
                <me>
                    \lVert\bv-\bw\rVert^2 = (\bv-\pr_V(\bv))\cdot(\bv-\pr_V(\bv)) - 2\bu\cdot(\bv-\pr_V(\bv)) + \bu\cdot\bu
                </me>.
                Recalling that <m>\bv-\pr_V(\bv)</m> is orthogonal to <m>V</m>, we see that <m>\bu\cdot(\bv-\pr_V(\bv))=0</m>. But then
                <me>
                    \lVert\bv-\bw\rVert^2 = \lVert\bv-\pr_V(\bv)\rVert^2 + \lVert\bu\rVert^2
                </me>.
                Since <m>\lVert\bu\rVert &gt; 0</m>, we conclude that <m>\lVert\bv-\bw\rVert^2 &gt; \lVert\bv-\pr_V(\bv)\rVert^2</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <p>
        Let's suppose that we have a collection of <m>m</m> data points <me>\bp_1=(x_{11}, x_{12},\ldots,x_{1n}, y_1),\ldots, \bp_m=(x_{m1},x_{m2},\ldots,x_{mn}, y_m)</me> and that our aim is to explain the values <m>y_i</m> in terms of <m>x_{ij}</m>, <m>1\leq j\leq n</m>. More formally, we are looking for a function <m>f:\R^n\rightarrow \R</m> such that <m>f(x_{i1}, x_{i2},\ldots,x_{in})</m> is fairly close to <m>y_i</m> for all <m>i</m>. The first <m>n</m> entries of the data points <m>\bp_i</m> are then called the <term>independent variables</term>, while the last one is called the <term>dependent variable</term>. The simplest kind of function that one could hope to have is linear. In other words, a function of the form
        <me>
            f(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_n)=a_0+a_1x_1+\ldots+a_nx_n
        </me>. In this situation, our task would be to find the coefficients <m>a_0, a_1, \ldots, a_n</m> that make the numbers
        <me>
            a_0 + a_1x_{i1} + a_2x_{i2} + \ldots + a_nx_{in}\quad (1\leq i\leq m)
        </me>
        as close to the numbers <m>y_i</m> as possible. 
    </p>      
    <p> Many different metrics can be used to assess the quality of the approximation. Perhaps the most widely used is the <term>sum of the squared residues</term>. If we fix a set of coefficients <m>a_0,a_1,\ldots,a_n\in\R</m>, the <m>i</m>th absolute residue <m>r_i</m> is defined to be the distance between <m>y_i</m> and the predicted value <m>a_0+a_1x_{i1}+\ldots+a_nx_{in}</m>: 
        <me>
            r_i=| a_0 + a_1x_{i1} + a_2x_{i2} + \ldots + a_nx_{in}-y_i|
        </me>.
        The goal of the least squares method is to find the coefficients <m>a_0,a_1,\ldots,a_n</m> that minimize the sum of the squared residues:
        <me>
            r_1^2+r^2+\ldots+r_m^2
        </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
        It will be useful to separate the values in our data points corresponding to independent variables from those corresponding to dependent variables. So let <m>\by</m> be the vector in <m>\R^m</m> whose <m>i</m>th entry is <m>y_i</m>:
        <me>
            \by=\colvec{y_1 \\ y_2 \\ \vdots \\ y_m}
        </me>.
        The independent variables will all be organized in a single <m>m\times (n+1)</m> matrix <m>X</m> where row <m>i</m> consists of the vector <m>(1,x_{11}, x_{12},\ldots,x_{1n})</m>:
        <me>
            X=\begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; x_{11} &amp; x_{12} &amp; \cdots &amp; x_{1n} \\ 1 &amp; x_{21} &amp; x_{22} &amp; \cdots &amp; x_{2n} \\ \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\ 1 &amp; x_{m1} &amp; x_{m2} &amp; \cdots &amp; x_{mn}\end{pmatrix}
        </me>.
        Using the vector <m>\by</m> and the matrix <m>X</m>, we can rewrite the square residue minimization condition in the following form: we are trying to find the vector <m>\ba=\colvec{a_0\\a_1\\ \vdots\\a_n}</m> in <m>\R^{n+1}</m> that minimizes the distance between <m>X\ba</m> and <m>\by</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        This is where projections come in handy. What we are trying to do is to find the closest vector in <m>V=\Img(X)</m> to <m>\by</m>. <xref ref="prop-dist-proj"/> tells us that that vector is precisely <m>\pr_V(\by)</m>. Therefore, we want to solve
        <me>
            X\ba=\pr_V(\by)
        </me>.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-normal-equation">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The vector <m>\ba\in\R^{n+1}</m> satisfies <m>X\ba=\pr_V(\by)</m> if and only if it satisfies <m>X^TX\ba=X^T\by</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Suppose that we have <m>X\ba=\pr_V(\by)</m>. Then
                <me>
                    X^TX\ba = X^T\pr_V(\by)
                </me>.
                We know that <m>\bu=\by-\pr_V(\by)</m> is orthogonal to <m>V</m>. <xref ref="exercise-transpose-kernel"/> states that the kernel of <m>X^T</m> is the orthogonal complement of <m>\Img(X)</m> in <m>\R^m</m>. Since <m>\bu</m> is in the orthogonal complement of <m>\Img(X)</m>, we conclude that <m>X^T\bu=\bz</m>. But this means that <m>X^T\by=X^T\pr_V(\by)</m>. So, <m>X^TX\ba=X^T\pr_V(\by)=X^T\by</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                We now prove the converse. Suppose that <m>X^TX\ba=X^T\by</m>. Rewriting the equation, we get
                <me>
                    X^T(X\ba-\by)=\bz
                </me>.
                In other words, <m>X\ba-\by</m> is in the kernel of <m>X^T</m>. Since the kernel of <m>X^T</m> is <m>\Img(X)^{\perp}</m>, this means that <m>X\ba-\by</m> is a vector in <m>\Img(X)</m>. Again, writing <m>\by=\bu+\pr_V(\by)</m>, and using the fact that <m>\bu\in\Img(X)^{\perp}</m>, we conclude that <m>X\ba-\pr_V(\by)</m> is in <m>\Img(X)^{\perp}</m>. However, <m>X\ba</m> and <m>\pr_V(\by)</m> are two vectors in <m>\Img(X)</m>, and so <m>X\ba-\pr_V(\by)\in \Img(X)\cap\Img(X)^{\perp}</m>. Therefore, <m>X\ba-\pr_V(\by)=\bz</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <example>
        <p>
            Consider the points <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,5)</m> and <m>(4,7)</m> in <m>\R^2</m>. Let's try to find the line of best fit, by which I mean the line <m>y=mx+b</m> that minimizes
            <me>
                |m+b-1|^2+|2m+b-5|^2+|4m+b-7|^2
            </me>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-least-squares-point">
            <caption>The points <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,5)</m> and <m>(4,7)</m>.</caption>
                <image width="80%">
                    <shortdescription>The points 1 comma 2, 2 comma 5 and 4 comma 7</shortdescription>
                    <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="prefig-least-squares-point">
                        <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                            <definition>p1=(1,2)</definition>
                            <definition>p2=(2,5)</definition>
                            <definition>p3=(4,7)</definition>
                            <coordinates bbox="(-1.5,-1.5, 8, 8)">
                                <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                                <point p="p1" />
                                <point p="p2" />
                                <point p="p3" />
                            </coordinates>
                        </diagram>
                    </prefigure>                    
                </image>
            </figure>
        <p>
            The values in the second entry of the vectors above correspond to the values of the dependent variable, so <m>\by=\colvec{2 \\ 5 \\ 7}</m> and
            <me>
                X=\begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 2 \\ 1 &amp; 4\end{pmatrix}
            </me>.
            The transpose is given by
            <me>
                X^T=\begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 4\end{pmatrix}
            </me>.
            The product <m>X^TX</m> is given by
            <me>
                X^TX=\begin{pmatrix} 3 &amp; 7 \\ 7 &amp; 21 \end{pmatrix}
            </me>.
            The linear system that we need to solve is
            <me>
                \begin{pmatrix} 3 &amp; 7 \\ 7 &amp; 21 \end{pmatrix}\colvec{b \\ m}=\colvec{14 \\ 40}
            </me>.
            The solution is 
            <me>
                \colvec{b \\ m}=\colvec{1 \\ \frac{11}{7}}
            </me>.
            So the line of best fit for this set of three points is <m>y=\frac{11}{7}x+1</m>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-least-squares">
            <caption>The points <m>(1,2)</m>, <m>(2,5)</m> and <m>(4,7)</m> and the line <m>y=\frac{11}{7}x+1</m>.</caption>
                <image width="80%">
                    <shortdescription>The points 1 comma 2, 2 comma 5 and 4 comma 7 and the line of best fit</shortdescription>
                    <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="prefig-least-squares">
                        <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                            <definition>p1=(1,2)</definition>
                            <definition>p2=(2,5)</definition>
                            <definition>p3=(4,7)</definition>
                            <definition>int=(0,1)</definition>
                            <definition>q=(7,12)</definition>
                            <coordinates bbox="(-1.5,-1.5, 8, 8)">
                                <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" />
                                <point p="p1" />
                                <point p="p2" />
                                <point p="p3" />
                                <line endpoints="(int,q)" stroke="orange" infinite="yes"/>
                            </coordinates>
                        </diagram>
                    </prefigure>                    
                </image>
            </figure>
    </example>
    
</section>